IMF Needs More Lagarde
Davos — Lagarde once said she is open to serving another five years as IMF Managing Director.
She should stay on.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she herself started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath damaged the credibility of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF restore its reputation.
Much attention has been focused on her personal qualities — as it should be.
She is candid, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries who met with her (often in delicate settings) expressed that she dares to speak the difficult truths while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate the terms of agreements rather than dominate them.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, or else firewalls had to be built to prevent financial contagion. The advice was unpalatable, but Europeans followed through.
Similarly, she strongly advocated for IMF support to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless more examples.
The IMF is not particularly good at innovation and is usually not full of passion.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution, which often prescribes bitter remedies, a more human face.
For example, managing the Middle East refugee crisis was originally not within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its programs to enable the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (more than one million people live in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak erupted in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in using available funds to provide debt relief to countries affected by the crisis, enabling them to improve the salaries of doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF used its capital in such a way.
Furthermore, Lagarde recognized that the world today faces three of the most important challenges and took action against them.
First, she strongly advocated for more women to join the workforce, and she herself serves as a role model demonstrating the value of women in leadership positions.
In countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a vast human resource — and thereby realize their economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
IMF research highlights a direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to prove this point, but its stature makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has personally been committed to promoting this point, which is key to the increased urgency.
Third, Lagarde has played a significant role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change—some of which will have frighteningly disruptive consequences.
For example, automation will continue to increase efficiency and reduce costs in manufacturing, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be lower than in the past.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth recognizing and carefully studying.
Lagarde has made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics would say it is time for developing country representatives to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European to hold this position in a row, and with Europe holding such privileges, it has become increasingly difficult to gain widespread acceptance in today's world.
Some would also argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded sufficient results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some would also point out that she faces allegations related to financial scandals in France, which would divert her attention from her work at the IMF.
Critics argue that the IMF must never again be distracted by similar scandals following the deep involvement of her predecessor, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, in a scandal.
Let's analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But ending this Western privilege aims to make the leader selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for IMF Managing Director, and emerging powers such as the BRICS countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not jointly nominated an alternative candidate.
Having Europeans serve as IMF Managing Director may also have been one of the favorable factors behind the IMF's decision last year to include the renminbi in the currency basket that determines the value of Special Drawing Rights.
In addition, Lagarde impressed with remarkable political flexibility, ultimately persuading both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve IMF governance reforms that not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal for containing financial crises but also more accurately reflected the evolving dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries have now entered the top ten shareholder list of the IMF.
On the Greece issue, Lagarde made some forthright — which some considered inappropriate — comments last year that reflected her personal style.
But she is certainly not the culprit behind the economic pain inflicted on the Greeks; her tenure at the IMF has clearly demonstrated that no IMF Managing Director in history has done as much as she has to lead the IMF in efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde in France were opposed by the French chief prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly such a leader, committed to making the IMF fit for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to see her work through from start to finish.
